<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec24-MatrixInverse" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Matrix Inverses</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In our journey through linear algebra, we have explored how to multiply matrices and how to represent systems of equations as the matrix equation <m>A\v{x} = \v{b}</m>. 
      A natural mathematical question arises: can we "undo" matrix multiplication? 
      In the realm of real numbers, we solve algebraic equations like <m>ax = b</m> by multiplying by the reciprocal (or inverse) of <m>a</m>. 
      In this section, we investigate whether a similar structural concept exists for matrices.
    </p>

    <objectives>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          After this section, students will be able to:
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            determine if a matrix is invertible; 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            find the inverse of a <m>2 \times 2</m> invertible matrix using a formula; 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            find the inverse of an invertible matrix using the Gaussian Elimination algorithm;
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            solve systems of linear equations using matrix inverses.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
  </introduction>

  <investigation>
    <p>
      Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
      Find a matrix <m>B</m> such that <m>AB = I</m> where <m>I</m> is the <m>2 \times 2</m> identity matrix. 
    </p>

    <hint>
      <p>
        There are two possible strategies: 
      </p>

      <p>
        <alert>Strategy #1: </alert> Guess and check! 
        This strategy is doable for a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix but usually quite tedious. 
        The matrix <m>A</m> is made special so that it isn't too bad at all. 
      </p>

      <p>
        <alert>Strategy #2: </alert> Remember how matrix multiplication works: 
        When we multiply <m>A</m> by <m>B</m>, each column of the answer is found by multiplying the corresponding column of <m>B</m> by <m>A</m>. 
      </p>

      <p>
        So we know that if <m>\v{b}_1</m> is the first column of <m>B</m>, then we will need <m>A\v{b}_1</m> to be <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> since that is the first column of the identity matrix. 
        If we call the entries of that column <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, then we can solve a system of equations to figure out what <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are!
      </p>

      <p>
        Then we can do a similar process to figure out what the second column of <m>B</m> is!
      </p>
    </hint>

    <solution>
      <title>Using Strategy #1...</title>
      <p>
        You probably discovered that the only way to get the <m>1</m> in the top left of the answer is to put a <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> in the bottom left of <m>B</m>. 
        Then you can figure out that you need a <m>1</m> in the top left of <m>B</m> to get the <m>0</m> in the bottom left of the answer. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Now you need a <m>0</m> in the top right of the answer. 
        because of the <m>0</m> in <m>A</m>, your answer for this spot will be <m>2</m> times whatever you put in the bottom right of <m>B</m>. 
        So that has to be a <m>0</m>. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Finally that <m>0</m> in the bottom right of <m>B</m> means that you need a <m>1</m> in your top right spot in order to get the <m>1</m> you need in the bottom right of the identity matrix. 
        So the matrix <m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
      </p>
    </solution>

    <solution>
      <title>Using Strategy #2...</title>
      <p>
        If we call our first column of <m>B</m> <m>\v{b}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}</m>, then we know that we need
        <md>
          \begin{cases}
            0x + 2y = 1 \\
            1x - 2y = 0
          \end{cases}
        </md>
        We can solve this using the substitution method easily since the top equation tells us <m>y = \frac{1}{2}</m> and substituting this into the second equation gives us 
        <md>
          x - 1 = 0 \qquad \implies \qquad x = 1
        </md>
        So the first column of <m>B</m> will have to be <m>\v{b}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ \frac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Now if we call our second column of <m>B</m> <m>\v{b}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}</m>, then we know that we need
        <md>
          \begin{cases}
            0x + 2y = 0 \\
            1x - 2y = 1
          \end{cases}
        </md>
        This one is even quicker to solve because the top equation tells us <m>y = 0</m> and substituting this into the second equation gives us <m>x = 1</m>. 
        So the second column of <m>B</m> will have to be <m>\v{b}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Therefore, the matrix <m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        And we can quickly verify that <m>AB = I</m>: 
        <md>
          \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>

    <p>
      Now that you found <m>B</m>, take a minute and compute <m>BA</m>. 
    </p>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <m>BA</m> is also <m>I</m>! 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </investigation>
  
  <p>
    This matrix <m>B</m> is a special buddy of <m>A</m>. 
    This is called the <term>inverse</term> of <m>A</m>!
  </p>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-InverseMatrices">
    <title>Inverse of a Matrix</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-inverse-matrix">
      <title>Inverse of a Matrix</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>A</m> is a square matrix, a matrix <m>B</m> is called an <term>inverse</term> of <m>A</m> if and only if <m>AB=BA=I</m>. 
          A matrix that has an inverse is called an <term>invertible matrix</term>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <p>
        <alert>An exmaple: </alert>
        <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}0\amp 2\\ 1\amp -2\end{bmatrix}</m> is invertible and <m>A^{-1}=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 1\\ \frac{1}{2}\amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m> since... 
        <md>
          \begin{bmatrix}0\amp 2\\ 1\amp -2\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 1\\ \frac{1}{2}\amp 0\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 1\\ \frac{1}{2}\amp 0\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}0\amp 2\\ 1\amp -2\end{bmatrix}=I
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        <alert>A non-example: </alert>
        <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}0\amp 0\\ 1\amp -2\end{bmatrix}</m> is NOT invertible because no matter what matrix you try you will get a row of zeros: 
        <md>
          \begin{bmatrix}0\amp 0\\ 1\amp -2\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}a\amp b\\ c\amp d\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}0\amp 0\\ \text{Doesn't}\amp \text{Matter}\end{bmatrix}
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-Uniqueness_Inverses">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A matrix can only have one inverse. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>B</m> and <m>C</m> are both inverses of <m>A</m>.
        Then 
        <md>
          AB=I \qquad \text{ and } \qquad AC=I
        </md>
        This means <m>AB=AC</m>. 
      </p>
          
      <p>
        Multiplying both sides of equation (on the left) by <m>B</m>,  we get 
        <md>
          B(AB)=B(AC)
        </md>
        Using the associative property, we get
        <md>
          (BA)B=(BA)C
        </md>
        Since we also know that <m>BA=I</m>, then <m>IB=IC</m>. 
      </p>

      <p>
        So by the identity property, <m>B=C</m>. 
      </p>
    </proof>

    <p>
      In the <m>2 \times 2</m> case, there is a quick way to find out if a matrix is invertible and there is a nice formula for the inverse. 
      We just have to define two terms: 
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-Determinant-2x2Matrices">
      <title>Determinant of <m>2\times 2</m> Matrices</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix. 
          The <term>determinant</term> of the matrix <m>A</m> is defined by
          <md>
            \det A = \det \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix} = ad - bc
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-Adjugate-2x2Matrices">
      <title>Adjugate of <m>2\times 2</m> Matrices</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix. 
          The <term>adjugate</term> of the matrix <m>A</m> is 
          <md>
            \adj A = \begin{bmatrix} d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a \end{bmatrix}
          </md>
          The adjugate of <m>A</m> can be obtained by (1) swapping the elements in the main diagonal, and (2) changing the sign of the elements not on the main diagonal. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      The matrix <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m> is invertible if and only if <m>\det A \neq 0</m>. 
      And<m>A^{-1}</m> is
      <md>
        A^{-1} = \frac{1}{\det A} \adj A = \frac{1}{\det A} \begin{bmatrix} d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a \end{bmatrix}
      </md>
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
        Notice that
        <md>
          \det A = (0)(-2) - (2)(1) = -2
        </md>
        Since <m>\det A \neq 0</m>, we know that <m>A^{-1}</m> exists. 
      </p>

      <p>
        We can also find <m>A^{-1}</m>. 
        We know that <m>\adj A = \begin{bmatrix} -2 \amp -2 \\ -1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
        Then
        <md>
          A^{-1} = \frac{1}{-2} \begin{bmatrix} -2 \amp -2 \\ -1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        If you want to verify that <m>A^{-1}</m> is indeed the inverse of <m>A</m>, try multiplying them together and you should get back <m>I</m>. 
      </p>
    </example>
    
    <p>
      Remember how we worked so hard to solve systems of linear equations in week 1? 
      And remember that every system of linear equations can be written as a Matrix Equation <m>A \v{x} = \v{b}</m> in week 2? 
      Well, if the coefficient matrix <m>A</m> is invertible, then we can solve this equation using <m>A^{-1}</m> just like back in Algebra 1! 
    </p>

    <p>
      Let's assume that <m>A</m> is invertible, then <m>A^{-1}A = I</m>. 
      Say we have a Matrix Equation <m>A\v{x} = \v{b}</m>. 
      We certainly can multiply the same thing (say <m>A^{-1}</m>) on two sides of the equation. 
      We get
      <md>
        <mrow>A^{-1} \lp A\v{x} \rp \amp= A^{-1}\v{b} </mrow>
        <mrow>\implies \qquad \lp A^{-1} A \rp \v{x} \amp= A^{-1}\v{b} </mrow>
        <mrow>\implies \qquad \qquad \quad \, \, \v{x} \amp= A^{-1} \v{b} </mrow>
      </md>
      So the solution to this equation must be <m>x\v{x} = A^{-1} \v{b}</m>. 
    </p>

    <p>
      If you want to verify that this is indeed a solution, then we can plug in <m>\v{x} = A^{-1}\v{b}</m> into the left side of our equation. 
      We see that
      <md>
        A\v{x} = A\lp A^{-1} \v{b} \rp = \lp AA^{-1} \rp \v{b} = I\v{b} = \v{b}
      </md>
      So this really is a solution to the equation! 
      Let's make it a theorem!
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-UniqueSolution-InvertibleMatrix">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>A</m> is an invertible matrix, then the Matrix Equation <m>A\v{x} = \v{b}</m> has exactly one solution. 
          The solution is <m>\v{x} = A^{-1} \v{b}</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    
    <example>
      <p>
        Consider the following system of linear equations: 
        <md>
          \begin{cases}
            3x + 2y = 5 \\
            5x - 8y = 14
          \end{cases}
        </md>
        The Matrix Equation version of this system is <m>A \v{x} = \v{b}</m>, where
        <md>
          A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \\ 5 \amp -8 \end{bmatrix}
          \qquad \text{ and } \qquad
          \v{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ 14 \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        Notice that 
        <md>
          \det A = 3(-8) - 2(5) = -34 \neq 0
        </md>
        So <m>A</m> is invertible! 
        We can find the solution using the little theorem we just came up with! 
      </p>

      <p>
        Since <m>\adj A = \begin{bmatrix} -8 \amp -2 \\ -5 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>, then we get
        <md>
          A^{-1} = \frac{1}{-34} \begin{bmatrix} -8 \amp -2 \\ -5 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{4}{17} \amp \frac{1}{17} \\ \frac{5}{34} \amp \frac{-3}{34} \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
        By our theorem, the solution to the system is
        <md>
          \v{x} = A^{-1}\v{b} 
          = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{4}{17} \amp \frac{1}{17} \\ \frac{5}{34} \amp \frac{-3}{34} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ 14 \end{bmatrix}
          = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -\frac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <p>
        Solve the following system of linear equation
        <md>
          \begin{cases}
            2x - 3y = 3 \\
            4x + 5y = 1
          \end{cases}
        </md>
        by
        <ol marker="1.">
          <li>
            <p>
              writing the system as a Matrix Equation; 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              finding the inverse of the coefficient matrix; 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              using the inverse to solve the system. 
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <solution>
        <p>
          1. The matrix equation is <m>\begin{bmatrix}2\amp -3\\ 4\amp 5\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}x\\ y\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}3\\ 1\end{bmatrix}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          2. The determinant is <m>22</m> and the adjugate matrix is <m>\begin{bmatrix}5\amp 3\\ -4\amp 2\end{bmatrix}</m>, so the inverse is 
          <md>
            \frac{1}{22}\begin{bmatrix}5\amp 3\\ -4\amp 2\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\frac{5}{22}\amp \frac{3}{22}\\ \frac{-4}{22}\amp \frac{2}{22}\end{bmatrix}
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          3. The solution is <m>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{5}{22}\amp \frac{3}{22}\\ \frac{-4}{22}\amp \frac{2}{22}\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}3\\ 1\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\frac{9}{11}\\ \frac{-5}{11}\end{bmatrix}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      There is another way to compute inverse matrices efficiently, which is using the Gaussian Elimination algorithm we learned back in <xref ref="sec12-GaussianElimination"/>. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Suppose we want to find the inverse of a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix <m>\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
      That is, we are looking for a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix <m>\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \amp x_2 \\ y_1 \amp y_2 \end{bmatrix}</m> such that
      <md>
        \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \amp x_2 \\ y_1 \amp y_2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
      </md>
      Since we multiply these matrices by multiplying the <m>\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m> by each of the column vectors <m>\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ y_1 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\begin{bmatrix} x_2 \\ y_2 \end{bmatrix}</m>, 
      the first matrix-vector product needs to give us the first column of <m>I</m> and the second matrix-vector product needs to give us the second column of <m>I</m>. 
      That means that finding the inverse boils down to solving two systems of equations given by the matrix equations: 
      <md>
        \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ y_1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
        \qquad \text{ and } \qquad 
        \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x_2 \\ y_2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
      </md>
      Observe that these two systems of linear equations have the same coefficient matrix. 
      So if we used augmented matrices, we would end up doing the same steps to put the matrices into reduced row echelon form. 
    </p>

    <p>
      The technique based on this idea is to put these two equations into ONE giant augmented matrix:
      <md>
        \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \amp \mid \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ c \amp d \amp \mid \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
      </md>
      But it gets even better! Let's do an example...
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Let's say we want to find the inverse of the matrix <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
        We will first make our big augmented matrix: 
        <md>
          \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 2 \amp \mid \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp -2 \amp \mid \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
        Now we will put this thing into reduced row echelon form! 
      </p>

      <p>
        Step 1: Swap Row 1 and Row 2, we get
        <md>
          \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -2 \amp \mid \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp \mid \amp 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
        We have our first leading <m>1</m> and it already has a zero beneath it. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Step 2: Multiply Row 2 by <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>, we get
        <md>
          \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -2 \amp \mid \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \mid \amp \frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
        Now the matrix is in row echelon form. 
        Let's get it into reduced row echelon form by getting a zero above the second leading <m>1</m>. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Step 3: Multiply <m>2</m> times Row 2 to Row 1 (and replace Row 1), we get
        <md>
          \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp \mid \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \mid \amp \frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
        Notice that the part on the left is the <m>2 \times 2</m> identity matrix. 
        And, notice that the part on the right is the inverse! 
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      That is basically the technique: 
      <ul marker="">
        <li>
          <p>
            Step 1: Make a big augmented matrix with <m>A</m> on the left side and <m>I</m> on the right side. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Step 2: Put the augmented matrix into <alert>reduced</alert> row echelon form. 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      If the matrix is invertible, then the reduced row-echelon form will have <m>I</m> on the left side and <m>A^{-1}</m> on the right side. 
    </p>

    <exercise>
      <p>
        Use the Gaussian Elimination algorithm to find the inverse of the matrix
        <md>
          \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 4 \amp 2 \amp -5 \\ 3 \amp 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
      </p>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The big augmented matrix is 
          <md>
            \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp \mid \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 4 \amp 2 \amp -5  \amp \mid \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 3 \amp 1 \amp -2  \amp \mid \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>First let's get zeros beneath our first leading <m>1</m>: 
          <md>
            \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp \mid \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp -17 \amp \mid \amp -4 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -11 \amp \mid \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Now we need to get our second leading <m>1</m> by multiplying Row 2 by <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>: 
          <md>
            \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp \mid \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{-17}{2} \amp \mid \amp -2 \amp \frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -11 \amp \mid \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Now we need a zero beneath our second leading <m>1</m>. 
          We can multiply Row 2 by <m>-1</m> and adding it to Row 3: 
          <md>
            \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp \mid \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{-17}{2} \amp \mid \amp -2 \amp \frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \frac{-5}{2} \amp \mid \amp -1 \amp \frac{-1}{2} \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Now to get our last leading <m>1</m>, we need to multiply Row 3 by <m>\frac{-2}{5}</m>: 
          <md>
            \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp \mid \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{-17}{2} \amp \mid \amp -2 \amp \frac{1}{2} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \mid \amp \frac{2}{5} \amp \frac{1}{5} \amp \frac{-2}{5} \end{bmatrix}
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Then we need to get zeros above this third leading <m>1</m>. 
          So, let's add <m>\frac{17}{2}</m> times Row 3 to Row 2 and -3 times Row 3 to Row 1: 
          <md>
            \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \mid \amp \frac{-1}{5} \amp \frac{-3}{5} \amp \frac{6}{5} \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp \mid \amp \frac{7}{5} \amp \frac{11}{5} \amp \frac{-17}{5} \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \mid \amp \frac{2}{5} \amp \frac{1}{5} \amp \frac{-2}{5} \end{bmatrix}
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          So the inverse is
          <md>
            \begin{bmatrix} \frac{-1}{5} \amp \frac{-3}{5} \amp \frac{6}{5} \\ \frac{7}{5} \amp \frac{11}{5} \amp \frac{-17}{5} \\ \frac{2}{5} \amp \frac{1}{5} \amp \frac{-2}{5} \end{bmatrix}
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-ImportantTheorems-Inverses">
    <title>Important Theorems and Facts about Inverses</title>
    
    <theorem xml:id="thm-CancellationLaw-Matrices">
      <title>Cancellation Law for Matrices</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>B</m> and <m>C</m> are matrices and <m>A</m> is an invertible matrix. 
          Then the following holds: 
          <ol marker="1.">
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>AB = AC</m>, then <m>B = C</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>BA = CA</m>, then <m>B = C</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Part 1: Suppose <m>AB = AC</m>. 
        Then 
        <md>
          <mrow> A^{-1} (AB) \amp= A^{-1} (AC) </mrow>
          <mrow>\implies \qquad \lp A^{-1} A \rp B \amp= \lp A^{-1}A \rp C </mrow>
          <mrow>\implies \qquad \qquad \quad \, \, IB \amp= IC \amp </mrow>
        </md>
        Therefore, <m>B = C</m>
      </p>

      <p>
        The proof of Part 2 would be similar. 
      </p>
    </proof>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-Transpose-Inverse">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>A</m> is invertible. 
          Then the inverse of <m>A^T</m> is the transpose of <m>A^{-1}</m>. 
          That is, <md>\lp A^T \rp^{-1} = \lp A^{-1} \rp^T</md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>A</m> is invertible. 
        Then
        <md>
          A^{-1}A = I \qquad \implies \qquad \lp A^{-1}A \rp^T = I^T
        </md>
        But <m>I^T = I</m> and <m>\lp A^{-1} A \rp^T = A^T \lp A^{-1}\rp^T</m>. 
        Substituting these into the above equation, we get
        <md>
          A^T \lp A^{-1} \rp^T = I
        </md>
        So the inverse of <m>A^T</m> is the transpose of <m>A^{-1}</m>.  
      </p>
    </proof>
    
    <theorem xml:id="thm-Product-Inverse">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are invertible matrices and <m>AB</m> is defined, then
          <md>
            (AB)^{-1} = B^{-1}A^{-1}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      This is also called "shoes and socks" because you take off your shoes and socks in the reverse order in which you put them on.
      That is what this theorem says about matrix inverses.
    </p>
    
    <proof>
      <p>
        <md>
          (AB)\lp B^{-1}A^{-1} \rp = A\lp BB^{-1} \rp A^{-1} = AIA^{-1} = AA^{-1} = I
        </md>
      </p>
    </proof>

    <p>
      There are also a collection of a bunch of facts about inverses (including some of the ones we have just mentioned). 
    </p>

    <p>
      Suppose the following matrices are all square and the same size. 
      <ol marker="1.">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>I</m> is invertible and <m>I^{-1} = I</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>A</m> is invertible, so is <m>A^{-1}</m> and <m>\lp A^{-1} \rp^{-1} = A</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are invertible, so is <m>AB</m>, and <m>(AB)^{-1} = B^{-1}A^{-1}</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>A_1, A_2, \ldots, A_k</m> are all invertible, so is their product <m>A_1A_2\ldots A_k</m>, and <m>\lp A_1A_2\ldots A_k \rp^{-1} = A_k^{-1}\ldots A_2^{-1}A_1^{-1}</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>A</m> is invertible, then so is <m>A^k</m>, and <m>\lp A^k \rp^{-1} = \lp A^{-1} \rp^k</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>A</m> is invertible and <m>k \neq 0</m> is a number, then <m>kA</m> is invertible and <m>\lp kA \rp^{-1} = \frac{1}{k} A^{-1}</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>A</m> is invertible, so is its transpose <m>A^T</m>, and <m>\lp A^T \rp^{-1} = \lp A^{-1} \rp^T</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>

    <p>
      It is super important to be able to tell whether a matrix is invertible. 
      One of the most important theorems in linear algebra i the <term>Invertible Matrix Theorem</term>, which identifies several conditions that are equivalent to a matrix being invertible. 
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-InvertibleMatrixTheorem">
      <title>Invertible Matrix Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The following conditions are equivalent for an <m>n \times n</m> matrix: 
          <ol marker="1.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>A</m> is invertible. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The homogeneous system <m>A\v{x} = \v{0}</m> has only the trivial solution <m>\v{x} = \v{0}</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>A</m> can be carried to the identity matrix <m>I</m> by elementary row operations. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The system <m>A\v{x} = \v{b}</m> has at least one solution <m>\v{x}</m> for every choice of column <m>\v{b}</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                There exists an <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>C</m> such that <m>AC = I</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\rank A = n</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    
    <p>
      If you Google the Invertible Matrix Theorem, there are a lot more equivalent conditions than what we have listed here. 
      Some of them are just rephrasing the conditions using other terminology and some of them requires a bit more linear algebra concepts that we are building towards. 
      We will certainly circle back to this theorem and add more conditions when we learn more! 
    </p>
    
  </subsection>

</section>